&lt;p&gt;When handling high-concurrency scenarios in Spring applications, proper use of asynchronous programming and thread pool management is crucial. This article provides an in-depth analysis of Spring&amp;rsquo;s default thread pool, custom thread pools, and thread reuse mechanisms through practical code examples.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="why-use-custom-thread-pools"&gt;Why Use Custom Thread Pools?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When a Spring Boot application starts, it automatically configures a global task executor (TaskExecutor) with the default name &lt;code&gt;applicationTaskExecutor&lt;/code&gt;. However, &lt;strong&gt;using Spring&amp;rsquo;s default thread pool directly in production environments is not recommended&lt;/strong&gt; for the following reasons:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>[Spring] 1. Spring Web CompletionStage Overview</title><link>https://gooddayday.github.io/en/2025/09/spring-1.-spring-web-completionstage/</link><pubDate>Sun, 21 Sep 2025 23:23:17 +0800</pubDate><author>865700600@qq.com (GoodyHao)</author><guid>https://gooddayday.github.io/en/2025/09/spring-1.-spring-web-completionstage/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction"&gt;Introduction&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Spring-web provides excellent support for asynchronous operations, which can be used for many optimizations through asynchronous return forms:
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Improve throughput&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Fine-tune execution thread pools for various business operations&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
